<font color="#FF0000">MR. QUAN, MIKE AND ME</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 19 11:59:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All<br>
I wrote this e-mail to a fellow vet about three weeks ago when I was feeling low. His response was that he would like to see this shared with others.  At the time, I came up with ten reasons why I shouldn't, but mostly, because I am protective of Mr. Quan. But I made enough changes to protect him without changing his story. Or mine.  So, to honour Mike and Mr. Quan, here it is.  I apologize that it is not 'Nam related, or, maybe it is.  You decide.<br><br>
Mike,<br><br>
One name not uttered<br>
one story untold<br>
Is one soul lost<br>
and one added stone<br>
to the road to oblivion.<br><br>
Thirteen years ago, I took a religion class at our community college. The instructor was a first generation Chinese immigrant who went by the name of Mr. Quan.  When I met him, he was thin, graying, with a slightly stooped posture. He looked old and ancient.  His accent was thick and many in the class which he taught complained about not being to understand him very well. I had no such problem.<br><br>
There was something about Mr. Quan.  I didn't know what then, but I was drawn to him, so much, that, I neglected another course so I could spend time with him.  We spent many, many hours, in his office, talking about religions, philosophy, about existentialism, about ping-pong, about anything that I could use to gain his interest.  I wish I could say that we had debates, but our talks were built on our similarities.  When we struck on these similarities, his eyes would light up and sparkle and there would be an enthusism that I see in my own daughter, a child-like excitment.  It was easy to see that he enjoyed life dearly.<br><br>
I knew that he was from mainland China and even the providence where he was raised.  I knew a little bit about his wife and children, but I didn't know about him.  He was a modest man.  I asked him to tell me about himself, and he would reply, &quot;You don't want to know about me, there are many more interesting people in the world.&quot;  And then he<br>
changed the subject.  On the last day of the semester, early afternoon, I asked him again and his reply was the same.  I told him that I needed to know and he asked why.  &quot;I don't know, I just know that that is what I need&quot;.  He just looked at me, took off his reading glasses and started his story.<br><br>
When he was younger, in his mid teens, his whole family moved to Malaysia, in Indonesia.  He had supposed that it was to get away from the civil war.  His parents, grandparents, eight brothers and two sisters and a couple of aunts and uncles.  Shortly after, Japan invaded China.  Japan began its quest of controlling all of southeast Asia and Indonesia.  When they captured Malaysia, all Chinese nationals were placed in concentration camps.  That included Mr. Quan and his entire Family.<br><br>
He described the living conditions, the food or lack of, the brutality. He described the forced labor and the torture they were subjected to.  And of the executions.  Over the period of four years in the camp, his entire family were beheaded.  Each time one was executed, the remainder of the family were forced to watch.  The ones to go first was the ones who could do the least work.  The elders were beheaded first, then the younger children until there was no one left but Mr. Quan.<br><br>
The camp was liberated.  Mr. Quan came to the U.S. after the war, recieved his education, worked many different labor type of jobs.  The rest of the story, I don't remember.  The details I don't remember.<br><br>
When he had finished with his story, it was getting dark.  He rushed me out, muttering something about his wife killing him for being late.<br><br>
The next couple of days, I stayed home.  I was sorely depressed.  Afterwards, I scoured the county looking for Viktor Frankl's book, &quot;Man's Search For Meaning&quot;.<br><br>
A couple of months previously, I received my awards from the Department of the Army.<br><br>
The next day, I composed the poem, wrote it in the book, and with my Bronze Star with &quot;V&quot; device and Two Oak Leaf Clusters, I went down to the school, presented the medal and the book to him.  I never saw him again.<br><br>
Until today. <br><br>
I went down to the campus, found that he was in a class and parked my truck as close to the classroom as possible.  Eventually the class ended and after the younger people dispersed, out came Mr. Quan.  He was totally gray and balding, even more stooped and ancient.  He shuffled in<br>
his walk. When he started to pass my truck, I got out and approached.  I called his name and he looked at me with a questioning face.  He didn't recognize me.  I told him my name and before I could finish pronouncing my name, his eyes lit up as I remembered them to do. He gave a yelp, reached for me and gave me a hug rivaling many stronger and younger men. He literally dragged me to his office and there he started talking about the book I had given him that many years ago.  He said that while he read the book about Viktor Frankl's internment in Auschwitz for three years, he realized &quot;That was me, that was me!&quot;  I agreed.  We talked<br>
more and he brought up the medal and our past conversations. He was so excited, his eyes wide open, and that sparkle. We spoke of his wife, grand kids, what I was doing and other chit-chat.<br><br>
In a pause (he was out of breath), I told him that he should write down his experiences.  He asked, &quot;Why?&quot;  I told him so that others may remember.  He said that there were many people with similar experiences. I told him that I only knew him.  He said that in the end, it didn't matter, that when he meets God, God would know.  I told him that God already knew, other people needed to know.  I told him that I couldn't remember all of the story, I couldn't pass it on to others in its entirety.  He asks who needed to know.  I said, &quot;I do, my daughter does!&quot;  He kept saying that it didn't matter.<br><br>
I left, deeply saddened at the loss.  Tonight, I grieve for that loss.<br><br>
your friend,<br>
Doc Del<br>

